{# templates/index.html.twig #}
{#--------------------------------#}

{% extends "_layout.html.twig" %}
{#--------------------------------#}

{% block title %}2G3G4G Home{% endblock %}

{#--------------------------------#}


{% block style %}
    <style>
        @import "css/bootstrap.min.css";
        @import "css/custom.css";
    </style>
{% endblock %}

{% block main %}
<main>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-md-8 col-sm-12">

            <ol class="breadcrumb">
                <li class="active">Home</li>
            </ol>
            <h1>Welcome to 2G3G4G Network</h1>
            <div class="jumbotron">
                <p>The purpose of this site is twofold.</p>
                <p>Firstly, it simulates the processes followed by Customer Care Representatives of a Mobile Phone Network, when reporting faults highlighted by Customers.</p>
                <p>Secondly, it simulates the job undertaken by Field Engineers in responding to reported faults and in resetting of mobile sites.</p>
            </div>
            <p>Mobile Cellular Networks can be made up of a collection of thousands of Sites. In reality, site performance can be affected in multiple ways. The most common being radio equipment failure, electrical faults, weather and line of sight issues.</p>
            <p>Sites are daisy-chained together in links, so if one sight goes off air at the head of a link, multiple sites coming off it will also go off air.</p>
            <p>In using this site a Customer Care Rep would be able to establish the approximate location of a fault experienced by a customer and compare it to the status of the mobile sites on the network, whether they are on air or not. The rep can establish the type of terrain that is in the approximate area of the fault as this might have an effect on Site performance. Reported Faults are then readable by Field Engineers who can log in to see and update faults related to their region, as well as reset sites on a link</p>

        </div>
        <div class="col-md-4  hidden-sm hidden-xs">
            <div id="carousel-example-generic" class="carousel slide" data-ride="carousel">
                <!--Carousel Indicators-->
                <ol class="carousel-indicators">
                    <li data-target="#carousel-example-generic" data-slide-to="0" class="active"></li>
                    <li data-target="#carousel-example-generic" data-slide-to="1"></li>
                    <li data-target="#carousel-example-generic" data-slide-to="2"></li>
                    <li data-target="#carousel-example-generic" data-slide-to="3"></li>
                    <li data-target="#carousel-example-generic" data-slide-to="4"></li>
                    <li data-target="#carousel-example-generic" data-slide-to="5"></li>
                    <li data-target="#carousel-example-generic" data-slide-to="6"></li>
                    <li data-target="#carousel-example-generic" data-slide-to="7"></li>
                    <li data-target="#carousel-example-generic" data-slide-to="8"></li>
                    <li data-target="#carousel-example-generic" data-slide-to="9"></li>
                </ol>

                <!-- Wrapper for slides -->
                <!-- Add the images and captions to carousel -->
                <div class="carousel-inner" role="listbox">
                    <div class="item active">
                        <img src="img/carouselc1.png" alt="Network Icon">
                    </div>
                    <div class="item">
                        <img src="img/carouselc3.png" alt="Mobile Phone">
                    </div>
                    <div class="item">
                        <img src="img/carouselc2.png" alt="Mobile Mast on top of Apartment block">
                    </div>
                    <div class="item">
                        <img src="img/carouselc4.png" alt="Mobile Phone">
                    </div>
                    <div class="item">
                        <img src="img/carouselc8.png" alt="Mobile Phone">
                    </div>
                    <div class="item">
                        <img src="img/carouselc5.png" alt="Mobile Phone">
                    </div>
                    <div class="item">
                        <img src="img/carouselc10.png" alt="Mobile Phone">
                    </div>
                    <div class="item">
                        <img src="img/carouselc6.png" alt="Mobile Phone">
                    </div>
                    <div class="item">
                        <img src="img/carouselc11.png" alt="Mobile Phone">
                    </div>
                    <div class="item">
                        <img src="img/carouselc9.png" alt="Mobile Phone">
                    </div>
                    <!-- Left and Right Arrow Controls -->
                    <a class="left carousel-control" href="#carousel-example-generic" role="button" data-slide="prev">
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-left" aria-hidden="true"></span>
                        <span class="sr-only">Previous</span>
                    </a>
                    <a class="right carousel-control" href="#carousel-example-generic" role="button" data-slide="next">
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-right" aria-hidden="true"></span>
                        <span class="sr-only">Next</span>
                    </a>
                </div>
            </div>
            <aside>
                <blockquote>IT'S GOOD TO TALK</blockquote>
            </aside>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-sm-12">
            <!-- list navigation for tabs -->
            <ul class="nav nav-tabs">
                <li><a href="#2Gb" data-toggle="tab"><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-phone"></span> 2G Network</a></li>
                <li><a href="#3Gb" data-toggle="tab"><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-phone"></span> 3G Network</a></li>
                <li><a href="#4Gb" data-toggle="tab"><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-phone"></span> 4G Network</a></li>
            </ul>

            <!-- TABS -->
            <div class="tab-content">
                <div class="tab-pane fade active in" id="2Gb">
                    <div class="row">
                        <div class="col-sm-5">
                            <p><img src="img/2G.png" alt="2G Network Diagram" id="networkDiagram2G" class="img-responsive"></p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="col-sm-7">
                            <blockquote>2G, first introduced in 1992, is the second-generation of cellular telephone technology and the first to use digital encryption of conversations. 2G networks were the first to offer data services and SMS text messaging, but their data transfer rates are lower than those of their successors.</blockquote>
                        </div>

                    </div>
                </div>
                <!-- Checkups -->
                <div class="tab-pane fade" id="3Gb">
                    <div class="row">
                        <div class="col-sm-5">
                            <p><img src="img/3G.png" alt="3G Network Diagram" id="NetworkDiagram3G" class="img-responsive"></p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="col-sm-7">
                            <blockquote>3G networks succeed 2G ones, offering faster data transfer rates and are the first to enable video calls. This makes them especially suitable for use in modern smart phones, which require constant high-speed internet connection for many of their applications.</blockquote>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <!-- Senior Pets -->
                <div class="tab-pane fade" id="4Gb">
                    <div class="row">
                        <div class="col-sm-5">
                            <p><img src="img/4G.png" alt="4G Network Diagram" id="NetworkDiagram4G" class="img-responsive"></p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="col-sm-7">
                            <blockquote>4G is the fourth generation of mobile phone communications standards. It is a successor of the 3G and provides ultra-broadband internet access for mobile devices. The high data transfer rates make 4G networks suitable for use in USB wireless modems for laptops and even home internet access. Due to the fact that 4G relies on IPv6 for referencing and communication with every node on the Radio Network, it has eliminated the need for BSC'S and RNC's. This is because IPv6 makes the concept of utilising a BSC or RNC as a Default Gateway to a "local network" unnecessary for minimising IP address wastage.</blockquote>
                        </div>

                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</main>
{% endblock %}

